A known result for hexagonal spirals (often derived from the construction method):
The sum of the 6 neighbors of a number $N$ in Ring $k$ is $6N - 6$, provided $N$ is not one of the 6 corner numbers of Ring $k$.

The corner numbers $C_j^{(k)}$ occur when the spiral reverses direction. These are the first number on each of the 6 segments of length $k$.
The segment lengths are $k$.
The corner numbers $C_j^{(k)}$ are the 6 points that maximize the distance from the center along the 6 directions.
The path sequence is $M_{k-1}+1, \ldots, M_k$.

For $k=1$: $M_0=1$. Path $2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7$.
If 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 are the segments of length 1, they are all corners.
$N=2$: Neighbors {1, 3, 5, 7, 8, 9}. Sum = 33. $6N - 6 = 12 - 6 = 6$. This formula fails for $k=1$.

